explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required to determine if OS_CondVarDelete contains dead code:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the initial conditional (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) can be true, and whether the call has side effects (e.g., initializes or mutates the token). If GetById can never return OS_SUCCESS or has no side effects, the conditional body might be dead.

- OS_CondVarDelete_Impl: The result of this call is immediately assigned to return_code and then possibly overwritten by OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete. To decide if the assignment or the call itself is dead, we must know whether the call has observable side effects (resource release, state change) or whether its return value is later used by finalize.

- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: This call overwrites return_code; to know whether the previous assignment from OS_CondVarDelete_Impl is dead, we must know if FinalizeDelete consumes/depends on the input return_code and whether it has observable side effects (so its presence/absence affects behavior).

- OS_object_token_t: The token object passed to Impl and FinalizeDelete may carry state or references that cause observable effects; its definition and lifetime are needed to see if any operations using it are necessary.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_CondVarDelete_Impl (per call graph). Understanding this helps determine whether OS_CondVarDelete_Impl has side effects (indexing, state changes) that would make that call non-dead.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: FinalizeDelete calls this (per call graph); its semantics (committing/rolling back) determine whether FinalizeDelete is observable and whether earlier operations matter.

- OS_NotifyEvent: Also called by FinalizeDelete (per call graph); notifications are observable side effects — needed to assess whether FinalizeDelete (and thus the overwritten return_code) is required.

- OS_SUCCESS: Macro/constant value used to test the return from GetById; needed to reason about branch feasibility and whether the body is reachable/meaningful.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById that affect its behavior (access mode and object type). Their values or semantics may determine whether GetById can succeed and thus whether the body executes.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: These are callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById (per call graph). Their semantics can affect whether GetById has side effects, whether a token is produced/valid, and whether GetById ever returns OS_SUCCESS — all necessary to decide if subsequent calls are dead.

In short, to decide whether any operation in OS_CondVarDelete is removable without changing program behaviour, we must know (a) whether the conditional body can execute (GetById and its inputs/constants), (b) whether the Impl call has observable side effects, and (c) whether FinalizeDelete depends on the previous Impl return or produces its own observable effects (transaction finish, notifications). The listed symbols provide the necessary definitions and callee semantics to make that determination.
